{"title_page": "Arun Nigavekar", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2011}}\n'''Arun Nigavekar''' (born 1942) is an [[India]]n [[physicist]] and [[Educational sciences|educator]]. He was the vice-chancellor of the [[University of Pune]] from 1998 to 2000 and the vice-chairperson and then chairperson of the [[University Grants Commission (India)|University Grants Commission]] (UGC) from 2000 to 2005.<ref name=\"Punechancellor\">{{cite web|title=Former chancellors|url=http://www.unipune.ac.in/university_files/vice_chancellorsList.htm|website=Pune university website|accessdate=5 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"UGCPresident\">{{cite web|title=Former commission members|url=https://www.ugc.ac.in/subpage/Former-Commission-Members.aspx|website=UGC official website|accessdate=5 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nNigavekar helped establish the [[National Assessment and Accreditation Council]] (NAAC) body as the Founder Director.<ref>{{cite web|title=Former directors|url=http://www.naac.gov.in/formerdirectors.asp|website=NAAC official website|accessdate=5 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711065125/http://www.naac.gov.in/formerdirectors.asp|archive-date=11 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam|A. P. J. Kalam]], the former [[President of India]], dubbed him as the 'Father of Quality Education in India'. {{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Early life==\nHe studied in Pune and Uppsala in Sweden where he held SIDA Fellowship.. He was awarded the Dakshina Fellowship by Rajaram College in Kolhapur.\n\n==Career==\nHe helped advance the use of technology and internationalization of higher education. He highlighted the concept of Quality in Higher Education. He served as Vice Chancellor of University of Pune. He has 70 research publications to his credit.\n\nHe became a Professor in Materials Science in Pune University in 1977. He established the Center for Advanced Studies in Physics in Pune in 1980.\n\nHe served as Director of Educational Media Research Center and established Communication Science Department in Pune University in the 1990s.\n\nHe was Chairman and Vice Chairman of UGC (2000-2005). He helped formulate a strategy for higher education in the Tenth Plan of Government of India. .\n\nHe was a Visiting Professor in [[University of York]] in U.K. and [[University of Western Ontario]] in Canada in the 1980s. He was a founding editor of ''Physics Educational Journal''. He is a permanent member and was Vice-Chairman of Asian Physics Education Network, a [[UNESCO]] organization.\n\nHe was a member of UGC from 1993-1996 and initiated reforms such as decentralization of UGC administration. He was a founding Director of National Assessment and Accreditation Council, an autonomous body of UGC. He developed instruments and methodology for judging quality in Indian higher education, which was endorsed by International Network for Quality Assuring Agencies in Higher Education (INQUAHE). He was a member of Distance Education Council and an adviser to Commonwealth of Learning in Canada.\n\n==Recognition==\nHe was awarded Honorary Doctorates by [[Tilka Manjhi Bhagalpur University]], [[Acharya Nagarjuna University|Nagarjuna University]], [[Guru Nanak Dev University]], [[Jagadguru Rambhadracharya Handicapped University]], [[University of Calicut]] and [[Potti Sreeramulu Telugu University]].\n\nHe won the Phia Foundation Award, UNESCO honor, Swami Vivekanand Award, Advocate D R Nagakar Award, Shiromani Award and the Delhi Ratan Award.\n\nNigavekar has appeared in the ''Financial Chronicle'', ''Sakal'' (a [[Marathi language|Marathi]] newspaper), the ''[[The Times of India|Times of India]]'' and ''The Hindu''.\n\nHe heads the committee of experts appointed by the Union Public Service Commission (UPSC) to review the existing structure of Civil Services (Main) examination and suggest necessary changes.\n\nNigavekar heads a committee created by the Maharashtra State Government to formulate and implement a holistic conservation plan for historic lake Lonar.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-01-29/mumbai/28377154_1_lonar-lake-state-sets-expert-panels|title=State sets up expert panels for Lonar lake|work=The Times of India|access-date=2017-11-23}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nigavekar, Arun}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian educational theorists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian physicists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2011}}\n'''Arun Nigavekar''' (born 1942) is an [[India]]n [[physicist]] and [[Educational sciences|educator]]. He was the vice-chancellor of the [[University of Pune]] from 1998 to 2000 and the vice-chairperson and then chairperson of the [[University Grants Commission (India)|University Grants Commission]] (UGC) from 2000 to 2005.<ref name=\"Punechancellor\">{{cite web|title=Former chancellors|url=http://www.unipune.ac.in/university_files/vice_chancellorsList.htm|website=Pune university website|accessdate=5 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"UGCPresident\">{{cite web|title=Former commission members|url=https://www.ugc.ac.in/subpage/Former-Commission-Members.aspx|website=UGC official website|accessdate=5 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nNigavekar helped establish the [[National Assessment and Accreditation Council]] (NAAC) body as the Founder Director.<ref>{{cite web|title=Former directors|url=http://www.naac.gov.in/formerdirectors.asp|website=NAAC official website|accessdate=5 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711065125/http://www.naac.gov.in/formerdirectors.asp|archive-date=11 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam|A. P. J. Kalam]], the former [[President of India]], dubbed him as the 'Father of Quality Education in India'. {{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Early life==\nHe studied in Pune and Uppsala in Sweden where he held SIDA Fellowship.. He was awarded the Dakshina Fellowship by Rajaram College in Kolhapur.\n\n==Career==\nHe helped advance the use of technology and internationalization of higher education. He highlighted the concept of Quality in Higher Education. He served as Vice Chancellor of University of Pune. He has 70 research publications to his credit.\n\nHe became a Professor in Materials Science in Pune University in 1977. He established the Center for Advanced Studies in Physics in Pune in 1980.\n\nHe served as Director of Educational Media Research Center and established Communication Science Department in Pune University in the 1990s.\n\nHe was Chairman and Vice Chairman of UGC (2000-2005). He helped formulate a strategy for higher education in the Tenth Plan of Government of India. .\n\nHe was a Visiting Professor in [[University of York]] in U.K. and [[University of Western Ontario]] in Canada in the 1980s. He was a founding editor of ''Physics Educational Journal''. He is a permanent member and was Vice-Chairman of Asian Physics Education Network, a [[UNESCO]] organization.\n\nHe was a member of UGC from 1993-1996 and initiated reforms such as decentralization of UGC administration. He was a founding Director of National Assessment and Accreditation Council, an autonomous body of UGC. He developed instruments and methodology for judging quality in Indian higher education, which was endorsed by International Network for Quality Assuring Agencies in Higher Education (INQUAHE). He was a member of Distance Education Council and an adviser to Commonwealth of Learning in Canada.\n\n==Recognition==\nHe was awarded Honorary Doctorates by [[Tilka Manjhi Bhagalpur University]], [[Acharya Nagarjuna University|Nagarjuna University]], [[Guru Nanak Dev University]], [[Jagadguru Rambhadracharya Handicapped University]], [[University of Calicut]] and [[Potti Sreeramulu Telugu University]].\n\nHe won the Phia Foundation Award, UNESCO honor, Swami Vivekanand Award, Advocate D R Nagakar Award, Shiromani Award and the Delhi Ratan Award.\n\nNigavekar has appeared in the ''Financial Chronicle'', ''Sakal'' (a [[Marathi language|Marathi]] newspaper), the ''[[The Times of India|Times of India]]'' and ''The Hindu''.\n\nHe heads the committee of experts appointed by the Union Public Service Commission (UPSC) to review the existing structure of Civil Services (Main) examination and suggest necessary changes.\n\nNigavekar heads a committee created by the Maharashtra State Government to formulate and implement a holistic conservation plan for historic lake Lonar.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-01-29/mumbai/28377154_1_lonar-lake-state-sets-expert-panels|title=State sets up expert panels for Lonar lake|work=The Times of India|access-date=2017-11-23}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nigavekar, Arun}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian educational theorists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian physicists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arun_Nigavekar"}
{"title_page": "Arun Kumar Basak", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Arun Kumar Basak\n| native_name = \u0985\u09b0\u09c1\u09a8 \u0995\u09c1\u09ae\u09be\u09b0 \u09ac\u09b8\u09be\u0995\n| native_name_lang = bn\n| image = Arun kumar basak (cropped).JPG\n| caption = Basak in 2012\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1941|10|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Pabna]], [[Bengal Presidency]], [[British India]] (now [[Bangladesh]])\n| fields = [[Theoretical physics]], [[Atomic physics]], [[Nuclear Physics]]\n| workplaces = [[University of Rajshahi]]<br /> [[University of Kent|Kent University]]<br/> [[Shahjalal University of Science and Technology]]\n| alma_mater = University of Rajshahi<br />[[Rajshahi College]]<br />[[Birmingham University]]<br/> [[Shahjalal University of Science and Technology]]\n| influences = \n| known_for = \n}}\n\n'''Arun Kumar Basak''' (born October 17, 1941<ref name=star/>) is a Bangladeshi physicist. He is [[Professor Emeritus]] in the Department of Physics, [[University of Rajshahi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dept.ru.ac.bd/physics/faculty/current-faculty-members/|title=Current Faculty Members|work=ru.ac.bd|accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBasak was born in Radhanagor of [[Pabna]] town, [[Bengal Presidency]], [[British India]] to parents Haripada Basak and Usha Rani Basak.<ref>{{cite news |title=Year book of the Bangladesh Academy of Science |date=2014 |page=335}}</ref> Basak matriculated in 1957 securing First Division from R.M. Academy. He secured the second position in the merit list in the Intermediate Science Examination held under [[University of Rajshahi]] in 1959 from [[Govt. Edward College, Pabna|Edward College]]. He was placed in First Class with the first position in the B.Sc. (Hons) examination from [[Rajshahi College]] in 1961. In M.Sc. Examination (1963) from University of Rajshahi, he obtained the first position in first class and was awarded an RU Gold medal.<ref name=bas>{{cite web|url=http://www.bas.org.bd/fellowship/list-of-fellows-/userprofile/akbasak.html|title=Professor Arun Kumar Basak|work=bas.org.bd}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn December 1963, Basak joined the University of Rajshahi as a lecturer in the Department of Physics. In 1978, Basak was appointed as an Associate Professor by the [[University of Dhaka]], but he preferred to stay in Rajshahi where he became Associate Professor in the later part of 1978.<ref name=\"DUMAA\">{{cite book |last= DUMAA |title=Dhaka University Microbiology Alumni Association (DUMAA) News Letter and Science News |chapter=Professor Arun K. Basak: Emeritus Professor of Physics in Bangladesh |editor-last=Choudhury |editor-first=Prof. Shamima |location=Dhaka |publisher=Dhaka University Microbiology Alumni Association |date= 30 September 2011 |pages=5, 6, 8}}</ref>\nHe was awarded a merit scholarship for securing the highest marks in the Faculty of Science and got admission at [[Imperial College]], London. Owing to the 1965 Indo-Pak war, he could not avail the opportunity. In 1972, he went to the [[University of Birmingham]] with a [[Commonwealth Scholarship]]. He worked with the tensor polarized deuteron and the polarized <sup>3</sup>He beams, the latter being the only one of its kind in the world. He earned his Ph.D. degree in 1975.<ref name=bas/>\n\n===Professional membership===\n# Senior associate of the [[International Centre for Theoretical Physics]] at [[Trieste]], Italy during 1987-96. \n# Elected as a [[fellow]] of the [[Bangladesh Academy of Sciences]] in 2001\n# Elected as a fellow of the [[Institute of Physics]] ([[London]]) in 2001. \n# Was a principal investigator from Bangladesh in a collaborative project, which funded by the [[US National Science Foundation]]. \n# The fellow of Bangladesh Physical Society from 1987 (life membership).\n# A member of [[American Physical Society]] during 200-03 and from 2013(life membership).<ref name=star/>\n\n===Others===\n* Was a post doctoral fellow in [[Nuclear Physics]], The [[Ohio State University]], United States during 1981-82.\n* An associate member of [[ICTP]], Italy during 1888-1995.\n* Visiting scholar at [[Southern Illinois University]], USA in 1997.<ref name=star/>\n* Visiting Professor at [[Kent State University]], USA.<ref name=\"basak\">{{cite news |url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5y4xcD25a5cLUYtWl8yU2lCTnM/view?usp=sharing |format=PDF |title=Professor Arun Kumar Basak: A man with a difference |work=Probe |location=Bangladesh |date=2006-08-11 |page=11 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5y4xcD25a5cLUYtWl8yU2lCTnM/view?usp=sharing |archivedate=2016-08-12 |accessdate=2016-08-28 }}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* Bangladesh Academy of Sciences Gold Medal in Physical Sciences (2003)\n* Star Lifetime Award on Physics (2016)<ref name=star>{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/supplements/star-lifetime-awardees-2016/prof-arun-kumar-basak-212800\n|title=Prof. Arun Kumar Basak|date=February 5, 2016|accessdate=February 16, 2016|newspaper=The Daily Star}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://academic.microsoft.com/#/detail/2154657515 Top Publications of A. K. Basak]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Basak, Arun Kumar}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi physicists]]\n[[Category:University of Rajshahi alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Rajshahi faculty]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Birmingham]]\n[[Category:Bengali physicists]]\n[[Category:Nuclear physicists]]\n[[Category:Theoretical physicists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Bangladesh Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Physics educators]]\n[[Category:People from Pabna District]]\n[[Category:Rajshahi College alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Arun Kumar Basak\n| native_name = \u0985\u09b0\u09c1\u09a8 \u0995\u09c1\u09ae\u09be\u09b0 \u09ac\u09b8\u09be\u0995\n| native_name_lang = bn\n| image = Arun kumar basak (cropped).JPG\n| caption = Basak in 2012\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1941|10|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Pabna]], [[Bengal Presidency]], [[British India]] (now [[Bangladesh]])\n| fields = [[Theoretical physics]], [[Atomic physics]], [[Nuclear Physics]]\n| workplaces = [[University of Rajshahi]]<br /> [[University of Kent|Kent University]]<br/> [[Shahjalal University of Science and Technology]]\n| alma_mater = University of Rajshahi<br />[[Rajshahi College]]<br />[[Birmingham University]]<br/> [[Shahjalal University of Science and Technology]]\n| influences = \n| known_for = \n}}\n\n'''Arun Kumar Basak''' (born October 17, 1941<ref name=star/>) is a Bangladeshi physicist. He is [[Professor Emeritus]] in the Department of Physics, [[University of Rajshahi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dept.ru.ac.bd/physics/faculty/current-faculty-members/|title=Current Faculty Members|work=ru.ac.bd|accessdate=February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBasak was born in Radhanagor of [[Pabna]] town, [[Bengal Presidency]], [[British India]] to parents Haripada Basak and Usha Rani Basak.<ref>{{cite news |title=Year book of the Bangladesh Academy of Science |date=2014 |page=335}}</ref> Basak matriculated in 1957 securing First Division from R.M. Academy. He secured the second position in the merit list in the Intermediate Science Examination held under [[University of Rajshahi]] in 1959 from [[Govt. Edward College, Pabna|Edward College]]. He was placed in First Class with the first position in the B.Sc. (Hons) examination from [[Rajshahi College]] in 1961. In M.Sc. Examination (1963) from University of Rajshahi, he obtained the first position in first class and was awarded an RU Gold medal.<ref name=bas>{{cite web|url=http://www.bas.org.bd/fellowship/list-of-fellows-/userprofile/akbasak.html|title=Professor Arun Kumar Basak|work=bas.org.bd}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn December 1963, Basak joined the University of Rajshahi as a lecturer in the Department of Physics. In 1978, Basak was appointed as an Associate Professor by the [[University of Dhaka]], but he preferred to stay in Rajshahi where he became Associate Professor in the later part of 1978.<ref name=\"DUMAA\">{{cite book |last= DUMAA |title=Dhaka University Microbiology Alumni Association (DUMAA) News Letter and Science News |chapter=Professor Arun K. Basak: Emeritus Professor of Physics in Bangladesh |editor-last=Choudhury |editor-first=Prof. Shamima |location=Dhaka |publisher=Dhaka University Microbiology Alumni Association |date= 30 September 2011 |pages=5, 6, 8}}</ref>\nHe was awarded a merit scholarship for securing the highest marks in the Faculty of Science and got admission at [[Imperial College]], London. Owing to the 1965 Indo-Pak war, he could not avail the opportunity. In 1972, he went to the [[University of Birmingham]] with a [[Commonwealth Scholarship]]. He worked with the tensor polarized deuteron and the polarized <sup>3</sup>He beams, the latter being the only one of its kind in the world. He earned his Ph.D. degree in 1975.<ref name=bas/>\n\n===Professional membership===\n# Senior associate of the [[International Centre for Theoretical Physics]] at [[Trieste]], Italy during 1987-96. \n# Elected as a [[fellow]] of the [[Bangladesh Academy of Sciences]] in 2001\n# Elected as a fellow of the [[Institute of Physics]] ([[London]]) in 2001. \n# Was a principal investigator from Bangladesh in a collaborative project, which funded by the [[US National Science Foundation]]. \n# The fellow of Bangladesh Physical Society from 1987 (life membership).\n# A member of [[American Physical Society]] during 200-03 and from 2013(life membership).<ref name=star/>\n\n===Others===\n* Was a post doctoral fellow in [[Nuclear Physics]], The [[Ohio State University]], United States during 1981-82.\n* An associate member of [[ICTP]], Italy during 1888-1995.\n* Visiting scholar at [[Southern Illinois University]], USA in 1997.<ref name=star/>\n* Visiting Professor at [[Kent State University]], USA.<ref name=\"basak\">{{cite news |url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5y4xcD25a5cLUYtWl8yU2lCTnM/view?usp=sharing |format=PDF |title=Professor Arun Kumar Basak: A man with a difference |work=Probe |location=Bangladesh |date=2006-08-11 |page=11 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B5y4xcD25a5cLUYtWl8yU2lCTnM/view?usp=sharing |archivedate=2016-08-12 |accessdate=2016-08-28 }}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* Bangladesh Academy of Sciences Gold Medal in Physical Sciences (2003)\n* Star Lifetime Award on Physics (2016)<ref name=star>{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/supplements/star-lifetime-awardees-2016/prof-arun-kumar-basak-212800\n|title=Prof. Arun Kumar Basak|date=February 5, 2016|accessdate=February 16, 2016|newspaper=The Daily Star}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://academic.microsoft.com/#/detail/2154657515 Top Publications of A. K. Basak]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Basak, Arun Kumar}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi physicists]]\n[[Category:University of Rajshahi alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Rajshahi faculty]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Birmingham]]\n[[Category:Bengali physicists]]\n[[Category:Nuclear physicists]]\n[[Category:Theoretical physicists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Bangladesh Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Physics educators]]\n[[Category:People from Pabna District]]\n[[Category:Rajshahi College alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arun_Kumar_Basak"}
